column1: Information: This spreadsheet contains a list of published ZooMS markers for different taxa. Note this is a ‘living’ document and will continue to be updated as new ZooMS data becomes available. Reference to the original publication reporting the marker can be found in the ‘Reference’ column and in the ‘Reference list’ tab. The nomenclature of markers include those proposed in Brown, S., Douka, K., Collins, M. & Richter, K. K. On the standardization of ZooMS nomenclature. J. Proteomics 104041 (2020). You are welcome to comment on this spreadsheet and share as widely as you like. Please contact Sam Presslee with any questions or comments: https://www.york.ac.uk/archaeology/centres-facilities/bioarch/facilities/zooms/

Note about fish collagen: Some species contain an ɑ3 chain in addition to ɑ1 and ɑ2. This trait is unique but not ubiquitous to fishes. Fish collagen also contains slightly higher concentrations of R and K residues, which means that peptides homologous to mammalian peptides may be two tryptic peptides in fishes and one in mammals. For example, peptide ɑ2 793 (793 - 816) in black rat, Rattus rattus, is positioned at m/z 2143.1. In cod, this sequence is two tryptic peptides of m/z 1186 (ɑ2 793 - 806) and m/z 898 (ɑ2 807 - 816) (Virginia Harvey)
